Post_ID: 2767863214936816650	|Post_Code: CZpbO3hLfwK	|Owner_ID: 22580829951	|Likes: 6	|Time_Stamp: 1644175029	|Tags: ['#Mournes', '#Mournes', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#mountains', '#outdoors', '#walking', '#hiking', '#leavenotrace']	|Caption: Graffiti in the #Mournes <br>This picture is of a handrail we replaced last year at a gateway to the Trassey valley. As well as having rotted away, the previous support was covered in graffiti, apparently documenting dates a particular couple visited. The same has occurred on the new rail despite previous etchings having been sanded off. The occurrence is not isolated to this location and the same initials (and occasionally the apparently corresponding names, Glen and Elaine) have appeared on stiles, way markers and other surfaces throughout the #Mournes. We are pleased to note that graffiti is not a particular issue in the area, but it would be sad if it became the case. As well as creating work for our small team who maintain the visitor infrastructure, feedback from other visitors is overwhelmingly clear that this - and other memorials/ markings ‚Äì intrude significantly on the experience of enjoying an unspoiled landscape. We appreciate that the practice is motivated for this couple by a love of the Mournes as well as each other but would suggest that appreciation of the place is best observed by a #LeaveNoTrace approach. Perhaps photographs and a diary for recording the other love? If you happen to see this Elaine and Glen, we wish you every happiness and ask that you enjoy future visits to the Mournes without visibly marking them. #mountains #outdoors #walking #hiking #leavenotrace

In areas that experience high levels of visitation, such as the campground or the Bear Gulch Reservoir, ground squirrels have become habituated to seek food from humans.<br><br>Never feed squirrels or any wildlife you find in Pinnacles, and maintain a respectful distance from them when possible.<br><br>Remember to always pack out what you pack in, and use our wildlife-proof garbage and recycling containers to dispose of waste, ensuring the lid is latched afterwards.<br><br>Do you have a Pinnacles haiku to help your fellow visitors plan for our learn about the park? A common strategy is to hike down from the plateau and cache water at designated camps before cycling. I did this for two campsites (two separate round trip hikes for each campsite) which gives an awesome perspective of the riding to come. Short, chilly days and long cold nights are another challenge to contend with in the winter, but the total absence of crowds is the reward for braving the low temps, I had the entire place to myself to freeze my ass off alone for three days. <br><br>Regardless of the direction chosen, the loop starts by dropping ‚Äúinto‚Äù the rim zone and finishes with a climb back ‚Äúout‚Äù, and one really does have the impression of entering into another realm, separated from the world above.  But the trip is more than the sum of it's distances and elevation change. Anyone who's read Calvin and Hobbes might remember Calvin's intrepid alter-ego, Spaceman Spiff, ever crash-landing on barren, alien worlds of cliffs, buttes, improbable rock spires, and monsters! Alas, no monsters to be had (only huge ravens a few Bighorn Sheep), but one does get a sense of exploring an planet in it's primal, formative state. You become (or should become) very aware of your gear, essentially your life-support, your water supply, your level of energy or fatigue, the distances separating you from camp, from water, from warmth, from safety. It is one of those all-to-rare places where you really feel like you are on a dynamic and indifferent planet, our own, not a sanitized, secured terrarium for Homo Sapiens. <br>(continued on next post...)<br>#bikepacking #bikepackingbags,  #ursusbikepacks, #faitenfrance, #artisansducycle, #konaexplosif, #Kona, #whiterimtrail, #canyonlands, #canyonlandsnationalpark, #canyonlandsnps, #leavenotrace, #utah, #moab

Post_ID: 2767121571819685661	|Post_Code: CZmymiiogcd	|Owner_ID: 45464644251	|Likes: 31	|Time_Stamp: 1644086618	|Tags: ['#bikepacking', '#bikepackingbags', '#ursusbikepacks', '#faitenfrance', '#artisansducycle', '#konaexplosif', '#Kona', '#whiterimtrail', '#canyonlands', '#canyonlandsnationalpark', '#canyonlandsnps', '#leavenotrace', '#utah', '#moab']	|Caption: Any cycling trip can elevate even a relatively mundane or familiar area to the realm of adventure, awakening or reawakening a deeper connection to, relationship with and appreciation for that land.  Bikepacking through one of the most spectacular landscapes imaginable, and those days in the saddle and nights in the tent can quickly become some of the most transcendent experiences one can have, a voyage that simply cannot be reduced to the metrics of maps and distances, one that takes place in you soul. <br><br>The ‚ÄúWhite Rim‚Äù (Canyonlands National Park, Utah) had been on my radar for a few years, as something I could do during one of my trips back to the US, usually in the winter to avoid the Las Vegas heat.  No wide angle lenses, HD screen, no poetry or prose can ever really capture what being immersed in such an environment is like. Nevertheless, I humbly offer my trip report and a few photos. <br><br>The route is only about 160km long, the riding is never very technical, and it is often ridden in a day by people much fitter or hurried than myself. I opted for two nights under that black sidereal canopy, a more leisurely pace leaving time for wandering, wonder, and contemplation.<br> <br>Vehicle access is via a vast plateau forming a kind of elevated peninsula stretching southward into the triangular confluence of the Green and Colorado rivers. This plateau is delimited by sheer bluffs with only a handful of roads and trails descending 400m down to the White Rim. From there, the route follows the characteristically whiteish, crumbling rim of even deeper chasms eroded away by the Green and the Colorado, which are only rarely visible along the route, mostly hidden by their own incisions that they've dug into the older, deeper layers of rock. <br><br>(continued on next post...)<br>#bikepacking #bikepackingbags,  #ursusbikepacks, #faitenfrance, #artisansducycle, #konaexplosif, #Kona, #whiterimtrail, #canyonlands, #canyonlandsnationalpark, #canyonlandsnps, #leavenotrace, #utah, #moab

Post_ID: 2767053924818275523	|Post_Code: CZmjOJXJMzD	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 495	|Time_Stamp: 1644078554	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#oldspanishtrail', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine']	|Caption: GC Petroglyphs 1, NM. This part of New Mexico may be the most historically and culturally diverse region in all of the United States in regards to the rock art that can be found here. The Old Spanish Trail ran through this land, bringing trade from New Mexico to California, which means lots of horses and pack mules, and lots of people traveling through these canyons. The recorded route began in the late 1700‚Äôs with explorers, Spanish military, and religious missionaries. Eventually trade became the primary reason people used the trail, often transporting regional merchandise, contraband, and slaves, and bringing back horses from California. Even before all this, indigenous peoples inhabited these canyons and thrived in this desert region, trading with the interlopers who passed through. This maze of arroyos and canyons is my favorite area to explore, and a vast mix of rock art can be found within the recesses of this topographic maze. Inscriptions from early travelers and wranglers, Navajo pictographs and petroglyphs, and Ancestral Puebloan glyphs all share the same sandstone canvases, often presenting a stunning visual timeline of the people who passed this way. And LOTS of horse inscriptions!<br><br>Slide 1- Antler Man has me stumped.<br><br>Slide 2- notice the horse and stag superimposed over each other.<br><br>Slide 5- Ancestral Puebloan polydactyl footprint<br><br>Slide 6- ‚ÄúNO 1000 HORSE OR MULE PACK‚Äù.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #oldspanishtrail #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine

Mostly sunny skies and increasing temperatures will put Loose Wet Avalanches on our problem list as temperatures warm today. Be aware of changing snow conditions as you travel today. Overnight temps below freezing will make for firm icy conditions and slide for life potential in steep terrain.  Be aware of your exposure and bring the proper tools (ice axe and crampons) in steep terrain, or stick to lower angel terrain with minimal hazards below you. Post_ID: 2766578192146568051	|Post_Code: CZk3DUyPRNz	|Owner_ID: 5636844661	|Likes: 1353	|Time_Stamp: 1644021842	|Tags: ['#AAGFilmFridays', '#TheAnselAdamsGallery', '#HorsetailFall', '#GalenRowell', '#AnselAdams', '#Yosemite', '#YosemiteNationalPark', '#LeaveNoTrace']	|Caption: It's about that time of year again...<br><br>Horsetail Fall season is just around the corner... Conditions permitting that is.  What is Horsetail Fall you may ask?  HF is a seasonal waterfall towards the east end of El  Capitan. Occasionally during mid- to late February, it can glow orange when it's backlit by sunset. This unique lighting effect happens only on evenings with a clear sky when the waterfall is flowing. Even slight haze or cloudiness can greatly diminish or eliminate the effect.<br><br>With how sunny it's been lately and the lack of recent precipitation, only time will tell if the phenomenon occurs.  If you are planning to visit the park during Horsetail Fall, expect very busy crowds.  With that being said, please practice Leave No Trace principles.<br><br>Leave No Trace - <br>1. Plan ahead and prepare<br>2. Travel and camp on durable surfaces (camping is not allowed at the Horsetail Fall viewing areas).<br>3. Dispose of waste properly<br>4. Leave what you find<br>5. Minimize campfire impacts (campfires are not allowed at the Horsetail Fall viewing areas).<br>6. Respect Wildlife<br>7. Be considerate of others<br><br>"With Yosemite, we have one of the most extraordinary places on Earth, but Yosemite possesses a "fatal beauty" which invites self-destruction unless we make a strenuous effort to control visitation and use." - Ansel Adams<br><br>Last Light on Horsetail Fall by Galen Rowell <br>https://www.anseladams.com/horsetail-fall-by-galen-rowell/<br><br>For information on Horsetail fall this year, please visit the site below. <br>https://www.nps.gov/yose/planyourvisit/horsetailfall.htm<br><br>#AAGFilmFridays #TheAnselAdamsGallery #HorsetailFall #GalenRowell #AnselAdams #Yosemite #YosemiteNationalPark #LeaveNoTrace

Post_ID: 2766478950356451418	|Post_Code: CZkgfKql4Ba	|Owner_ID: 253109645	|Likes: 41	|Time_Stamp: 1644010109	|Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT']	|Caption: Take a virtual, time-lapse hike through second-growth forest in the Arabia Mountain National Heritage Area.<br>.<br>What is second-growth forest? Most of the forests that stood when white settlers first arrived in Georgia were what's called "old growth," meaning stands of large, very mature trees without major clearing or logging. While the Muscogee did clear land and use timber prior to white settlement, of course, it was not at the same, massive agricultural scale. As the Georgia Piedmont was cleared for farmland - including by enslaved laborers, such as those at Flat Rock (@flatrockarchives) - many of these old growth trees disappeared. As farmland began to wane in the mid-1900's, some places have seen trees regrow. This is called "second-growth forest," or the forest the returns to a landscape following removal. <br>.<br>Not all second-growth forests come about because of human activity. In places that experience a severe wildfire or flood, second-growth forest arises once the disturbance has passed. In time, second-growth forest can become old growth forest again. As you walk through the woods in Davidson-Arabia Mountain Nature Preserve (@arabiaranger) and Panola Mountain State Park (@panolamountainstatepark), look at the trees around you. How young or old is this forest? Looking at the trees can tell you about the history of the land.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT

It means a lighter backpack, but less fuel for the trail.<br>.<br>üëâ OR a partial fuel container + another full fuel container. It means more fuel for the trail, but also added pack weight and less space for other necessities.<br>.<br>It's the ultimate #ultralightbackpacking catch-22. <br>.<br>üëâ We prefer OPTION #3 üî•: Combining two partially filled isobutane fuel canisters to make one full canister. It's why we launched the FlipFuel fuel transfer device ( www.flipfuel.co ). <br>.<br>‚ôª In addition to saving pack space and weight, the ability to refill stove fuel containers turns a single-use tool into a reusable one. It also means you can recycle the completely empty fuel canister. ‚ôª<br>.<br>Give us a like or a comment if you've ever experienced the "fuel canister catch-22"! Post_ID: 2766352557371564223	|Post_Code: CZkDv6BoCC_	|Owner_ID: 31495825161	|Likes: 38	|Time_Stamp: 1643994944	|Tags: ['#visitwales', '#snowdonia', '#leavenotrace']	|Caption: Whilst Winter is still here, we're continuing to refresh and reset by getting out into nature and embracing the elements. There's no better place to do this than Aber Falls; a spectacular waterfall nestled away on the edge of the majestic Carneddau Mountain Range. <br><br>The Aber Falls trail is a gentle, 3 mile family-friendly walking route. Located near the village of Abergwyngregyn between Conwy and Bangor on the A55, walkers can start on the trail from one of two car parks on the outskirts of the village. From here a gravel pathway meanders alongside the Afon Rhaeadr Mawr, through whimsical woodland and lush meadows from which walkers can catch the occasional glimpse of the falls ahead. As the trail nears the cliffside, the roar of the water cascading from 120 feet above fills the air. At the bottom of the falls the trail opens out to viewing points on both sides of the river, providing safe spots to admire the spectacle and feel the spray of the falls on your skin, the ultimate elemental refresh.<br><br>As always please remember to leave no trace behind you in order to help us preserve the beautiful, natural spaces we have on our doorstep if you're hoping to embark on this stunning walk through our national park and embrace it's wonders with us.<br><br>#visitwales #snowdonia #leavenotrace

It's about achieving a balance between human and animal well-being, economic benefits and environmental health, with a focus on maximizing the positive benefits for communities, animals, ecosystems and our beautiful planet! üíô<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Save this post if you want to travel more sustainably! ‚≠êÔ∏è<br><br>Keep your money local! The best way to ensure communities reap the benefits of your travels is by supporting local businesses and entrepreneurs. Consider staying in locally-owned B&B's, small boutique hotels, hostels or guesthouses rather than international chains. Dine at local restaurants and explore the local market. Book excursions led by local guides or learn a new skill from a local expert by signing up for a workshop or lesson üíÉüèºüí∏üå∂<br><br>Visit national parks, marine sanctuaries and other protected areas! They play an important role in the protection of biodiversity and natural resources. Many countries rely on entrance fees and operator permits to preserve these amazing places and protect the animals that live in it ü¶≠ü¶íü¶è<br><br>Slow down a little! Spending more time in one place makes for a more memorable, authentic and meaningful experience. It also reduces pressure on cities and communities while also creating greater benefits for local businesses ‚òÄÔ∏èüå¥ü••

Post_ID: 2766309487474613214	|Post_Code: CZj59KDt5ve	|Owner_ID: 4478084386	|Likes: 9	|Time_Stamp: 1643989823	|Tags: ['#stopplasticpollution', '#climatechangeisreal', '#notraceshop', '#switchtoreusables', '#conveniencekills', '#reducereusereycle', '#leavenotrace', '#compostable', '#compostathome', '#ditchdisposables', '#beeswaxwraps', '#veganwaxwraps', '#goingzerowaste', '#lowwaste', '#lowimpact', '#zerowaste', '#circulareconomy', '#zerowastebusiness', '#zerowastehome\u2060']	|Caption: You don't need to go out and buy a ton of stuff to start cutting your waste and living more green.  You probably already have a bunch of great options! ‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>But I often get asked about reusable alternatives to common things like ziploc bags or packaged tea or take-out containers.  And there are SO MANY reusable alternatives to our disposable lifestyle. ‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>Cloth snack bag or jar or beeswax wrap instead of ziploc bags; loose tea and tea strainers instead of packaged tea; pyrex or stainless steel containers that you take to the restaurant instead of disposable take out containers.  And so forth üòä.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>We have to be willing to let go of some convenience  and see the cost of convenience.  Maybe you have to do more dishes instead of throwing things out.  Or you have to (*gasp*) open your produce bag to see what's inside instead of having a plastic see-through bag.  In my view, it's worth the extra time and effort if it means preserving our planet and oceans and mitigating the impacts of climate change and plastic pollution.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>Click the link in my bio if you'd like to add a few wax wraps to your stash of plastic fighting super heroes üòâ. ‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>#stopplasticpollution #climatechangeisreal #notraceshop #switchtoreusables #conveniencekills #reducereusereycle #leavenotrace #compostable #compostathome #ditchdisposables #beeswaxwraps #veganwaxwraps #goingzerowaste #lowwaste #lowimpact #zerowaste #circulareconomy #zerowastebusiness #zerowastehome‚Å†

Post_ID: 2766255519094440040	|Post_Code: CZjtr0FloBo	|Owner_ID: 36076745073	|Likes: 12	|Time_Stamp: 1643983376	|Tags: ['#getoutside', '#hikemoreworryless', '#weekendwarrior', '#peoplewhoadventure', '#leavenotrace', '#utahisrad', '#moabutah']	|Caption: Although it's vitally important to follow Leave No Trace on every trail you find yourself on, the principles can often be forgotten on more popular trails that gather large crowds and hikers who are less experienced in responsibly getting outdoors. We put together a short list of some our of favorite LNT ethics to keep in mind when hiking to popular locations:<br><br>üèïSTAY ON THE TRAIL ‚Äì Although many people go their own way and cut switchbacks on popular&nbsp;trails, please stay on the official route and don't contribute to the formation of social trails which cause both erosion and drainage issues, and contribute to a loss of vegetation. Hiking in single file ‚Äì even when with a large group ‚Äì also helps prevent the trail from widening.<br><br>üèïPARK RESPONSIBLY ‚Äì Many popular hikes still only have small parking lots that fill up quickly during peak seasons. Do not park on grass, dirt, or other vegetation, and never block other hikers in. The unfortunate&nbsp;truth is sometimes hikers will have to turn around and come back to hike the trail later when the lot is full&nbsp;‚Äì in which case it really does pay to arrive early.<br><br>üèïDON'T BLOCK THE VIEW ‚Äì Imagine hiking multiple miles one way up a grueling mountain only to see that a fellow hiker set their hammock up right in front of the view point... don't be that guy. The view point is there for all to enjoy, so please be mindful and courteous when standing in the "iconic spot" and take turns with others for the best photo opts.<br><br>#getoutside #hikemoreworryless #weekendwarrior #peoplewhoadventure #leavenotrace #utahisrad #moabutah

However, what is unusual is the increasing frequency of ultra long dry spells since 2010. Today marks 30 days since it last rained greater than 0.08 inches in San Francisco city.  Prior to 2010 (encompassing 60 years of records) there were only four years where the mid winter dry spell exceeded 30 days, but since 2010 there are now five! What‚Äôs more, there is very high confidence it will stay dry for at least the next 10 days and likely longer. A 40+ day dry spell only occurred once prior to 2010 but if the forecasts verify this will be the third instance since 2010.  It‚Äôs very difficult to get an average season of precipitation when the winter dry spells are so long, and very difficult to escape multi-year droughts when these ultra long dry spells are occurring so frequently. In the past decade the core of wet season has effectively collapsed in the majority of years. #climatechange #californiaweather #cawx #keepitwild #californiawild #ventanawilderness #leavenotrace #recreateresponsibly #aridification

Road access to the backside ‚Äì which includes access to Get Carter, the Beehive area, and the Pollen Grains ‚Äì is still ice-covered and travel is not advised. <br> <br>While Buttermilk Road is passable up to the climbing area, it is still very rough and can cause a lot of wear-and-tear on a vehicle. Be mindful of your speed ‚Äì this will help protect your vehicle, limit road degradation, and respect others in the area. <br> <br>The Buttermilk Area is used by many user-groups. As such, it is an area where perceptions of the climbing user-group can be defined. Regional decision-making (that can affect our climbing areas) is sometimes informed by these perceptions. Making responsible decisions that are respectful of others goes a long-way. Beyond practicing respect and proper LNT behavior in the climbing area, how you drive on Buttermilk Road and how you park at the Buttermilk Area is very important to future decision-making. <br><br>If you come to the Buttermilk area this weekend, be mindful of your parking. <br>‚Ä¢ Do not park in a way that creates a traffic bottleneck. If a large, emergency service vehicle is not able to comfortably pass around your vehicle, park elsewhere. <br>‚Ä¢ Do not park next to, or across from the Whale boulder (the roadside boulder just south of the Peabodies) ‚Äì this creates the worst bottlenecks.<br>‚Ä¢ Do not park on any brush or drive through any brush to park.<br>‚Ä¢ Park nose-in at the roadside trailhead - this allows 10 cars to park instead of 4 to be parked parallel.<br>‚Ä¢ If none of these can be achieved, park further down the road and walk up ‚Äì this will help to prevent the congestion in the roadside area.

Post_ID: 2765724161295330865	|Post_Code: CZh03ikuS4x	|Owner_ID: 51175685665	|Likes: 8	|Time_Stamp: 1643920034	|Tags: []	|Caption: On a recent hike, I came across a muddy patch in my path. Because I want to be a responsible hiker, I've been learning the 'leave no trace' principles. I knew instantly to plow right through the mud and NOT walk along the side 'clean' path so as to not widen the path and contribute to erosion. I've accepted that a true hiker wears their adventures on their shoes. Mud, water, gravel, wet conditions are all environments my feet should be prepared for if I want to have a true hiking experience that leaves no trace and does not harm the area I'm hiking through.<br><br>Other 'leave no trace' principals I've learned and have had the opportunity to put into practice so far are:<br><br>üåøPack it out- putting apple cores and banana peels in a plastic bag I carry with me along with all other plastics/containers. I know to take all trash with me or dispose of properly in designated receptacles. It makes me sad to see discarded tires, plastics, and soda cans out in the middle of nowhere. This is home to other wildlife and we can do better.<br><br>Ethical and responsible hiking is extremely important to me as I continue to enjoy more adventures in our beautiful trails, national parks, parks, and other natural areas. Post_ID: 2765630358746952231	|Post_Code: CZhfiiJJfIn	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 497	|Time_Stamp: 1643908851	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#navajo', '#dinetah', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine', '#modernoutdoors', '#natgeoyourshot', '#natgeotravelpic', '#Yourshotphotographer', '#OurPlanetDaily', '#lonelyplanet', '#mylpguide', '#usinterior', '#bealpha', '#divine']	|Caption: SP Petroglyphs, NM. Very odd panel I found that I can‚Äôt really categorize. The rock it‚Äôs pecked into isn‚Äôt very patinated, so it‚Äôs hard to estimate age, but the glyphs look dark enough to be at least a couple hundred years old, and the application technique looks legit. This is one of those panels that looks like a complete piece, like all the details are part of a singular composition. I sometimes get caught up trying to figure out what culture a panel belongs to, but I need to remember that all this rock art was created by individuals, so trying to find common visual characteristics to help identify origin doesn‚Äôt always work. Sometimes people don‚Äôt fit into any category, and the same goes for rock art. Everyone has their place in the timeline, but some might not have fit the general cultural mold of that era. <br><br>Speaking of the panel itself, I can‚Äôt help but see a sunrise/sunset at the bottom. There are two zoomorphs, a snake and perhaps a sheep (you can see faint horns, but those may have been added later). The 15 crescent shapes are what really have me wondering. This one is just such an odd panel that doesn‚Äôt match up stylistically with any of the other panels that can be found in the area.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #navajo #dinetah #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

There's no better place to do this than Aber Falls; a spectacular waterfall nestled away on the edge of the majestic Carneddau Mountain Range. <br><br>The Aber Falls trail is a gentle, 3 mile family-friendly walking route. Located near the village of Abergwyngregyn between Conwy and Bangor on the A55, walkers can start on the trail from one of two car parks on the outskirts of the village. From here a gravel pathway meanders alongside the Afon Rhaeadr Mawr, through whimisical woodland and lush meadows from which walkers can catch the occasional glimpse of the falls ahead. As the trail nears the cliffside, the roar of the water cascading from 120 feet above fills the air. At the bottom of the falls the trail opens out to viewing points on both sides of the river, providing safe spots to admire the spectacle and feel the spray of the falls on your skin, the ultimate elemental refresh.<br><br>As always please remember to leave no trace behind you in order to help us preserve the beautiful, natural spaces we have on our doorstep if you're hoping to embark on this stunning walk through our national park and embrace it's wonders with us.<br><br>#visitwales #snowdonia #leavenotrace

Post_ID: 2765520781683309707	|Post_Code: CZhGn-jMbyL	|Owner_ID: 51456758866	|Likes: 13	|Time_Stamp: 1643895789	|Tags: ['#hikingtips', '#leavenotrace', '#familyadventures', '#hikingireland', '#familyhikes', '#top10', '#kidshiking', '#ourhappyhikers']	|Caption: Please share @ourhappyhikers tried and tested top 10 tips for happy hikes with kids:<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Hike often and stick with it: Try and hike at least once a month (we aim for every Sunday). And really important, expect and prepare for push back‚Äîbut if you are gentle, have distractions prepared for the journey (ask them what songs they'd like to listen to, have their favourite book/comic), and follow the tips below‚Äîwe promise, kids who complain as they shuffle reluctantly out the door always come good when they get on the trail<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Keep it easy: Start with easy walks, and keep them short. Pick a trail that has something interesting to aim for<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Take your time: If your kids want to stop and pick up and touch everything, this is one of the greatest things about hiking‚Äîso if they want to explore the undergrowth, then that is the new plan for the day‚Äîdon‚Äôt stress, there will always be a next time<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Prepare for anything: This pretty much goes for any hike but make sure to pack kid-friendly supplies: wet wipes or tissues; snacks, change of clothes, bug spray etc. Binoculars are a great carrot<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Dress well: Layers, waterproof shoes, rain gear, change of clothes‚Äîa hat and gloves packed even on a day that doesn‚Äôt seem that cold. Hikes can mean hills, and hills can be windy<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Have frequent energy stops: Tired kids can be cranky kids. Keep your child happy and motivated by setting targets for wholesome snack breaks. BRING WATER!<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Pick a leader: Kids love feeling they are in charge. Have them take turns leading the group, just make sure that the leadership rotates. Having your child lead can also mean they set their own manageable pace<br><br>‚≠êÔ∏è Make it fun: Create games (eye-spy), look for wildlife (squirrels, birds, fur) or spot wildflowers. It‚Äôs one of my least favorite things to do. But if I see poop nearby when my dogs are doing their business on a walk, I will bag it along with my dog‚Äôs waste. <br><br>Why? Because leaving dog poop on the ground wreaks havoc on our environment! <br><br>Some people think dog waste is a natural fertilizer - but it‚Äôs not! Dogs eat a high protein diet so their waste is highly acidic and can actually burn your lawn.<br><br>And dog waste left on the ground will eventually find its way into our local waterways through stormwater drains.  According to the EPA, dog waste contains two main types of pollutants that harm local waterways - nutrients and pathogens. Excess nutrients can cause algae blooms while pathogens can make local waters unswimmable and cause illness to humans who come in contact with them. <br><br>So let‚Äôs all pitch in and pick up after our pooches. <br>#pickupafteryourdog #reducepollution

The Waimea Canyon Trail trailhead is at the Pu‚Äôu Hinahina Lookout, where there‚Äôs parking and restrooms.<br><br>The views from the trail were beautiful. Post_ID: 2765090011169598995	|Post_Code: CZfkrcPvq4T	|Owner_ID: 4010258026	|Likes: 17	|Time_Stamp: 1643844437	|Tags: ['#ecofriendly', '#savetheplanet', '#leavenotrace', '#ecofamily', '#motherearth', '#slowlife', '#naturelover']	|Caption: My family does not practice Leave No Trace or discuss it with my kids. Why?&nbsp;<br>.<br>Apart from the role it currently plays in gate keeping the outdoors from marginalized communities, LNT emphasizes the idea that humans are visiting nature and not nature themselves. This separation is a root cause of so many of the environmental issues of today (as well as health issues, community failures, birth traumas etc). We see ourselves as outside of nature and therefore we can chose to care for it or not. But the truth is we are an interconnected part of nature and we need to live in communion with it.<br>.<br>So what do we talk about instead?<br>.<br>Respect: we talk about the world through the lens of animism and respect the myriad of other consciousnesses that are present. We talk to plants (and always ask permission before picking anything). We give offerings and say thank you to the lands and landscapes we move through. We respect animals by giving them space and honoring their experiences.<br>.<br>Reciprocity: what we get from the land plants or animals deserves care in return. This might mean stewarding a specific piece of land or offering water to a desert plant that we found a lizard living beneath or paying more for local produce.<br>.<br>Interconnection: we point out the ways all the beings of a land exist together. We don‚Äôt pick early spring wildflowers because they are an important food source for early pollinators. We pick up our garbage because it‚Äôs dangerous for wild animals to get used to eating human food.&nbsp;<br>.<br>Humans exist with nature: We pee outside because water is should cycle back to the earth. We are willing to walk off trail because most landscapes can handle a few small foot steps. We move with care and respect but not with fear that we are ruining something. The earth is meant to hold us. We are of her. &nbsp;<br>.<br>I do understand that human beings have negatively impacted the earth through their actions. I believe the healing the earth needs will not come from humans trying to ‚Äúsave‚Äù it, but instead, from humans who love and respect it as their home, their sister, their mother, and their love.<br>#ecofriendly #savetheplanet #leavenotrace #ecofamily #motherearth #slowlife #naturelover

@mountain_wilderness_intl The next Winter Olympics are just around the corner, and as usual we question the alleged sustainability of such mega sporting events, but this time we do so on the basis of scientific data.<br><br>Researchers at the University of Lausanne, Switzerland, recently reviewed the social, environmental and economic sustainability of 16 editions of the Summer and Winter Olympic Games.<br><br>The study concludes that the rhetoric of sustainability does not match actual sustainability outcomes and sustainability in the Olympics is clearly declining over time as Salt Lake City (2002) and Albertville (1992) scored higher than all the rest, whereas the Winter Olympics in Sochi in 2014 and the Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in 2016 had the lowest sustainability scores.<br><br>How will Beijing 2022 and Milano-Cortina 2026 score?<br><br>Link in bio<br><br>M√ºller, M., Wolfe, S.D., Gaffney, C.&nbsp;et al.&nbsp;An evaluation of the sustainability of the Olympic Today we're exploring the Saguaro Wilderness in <br>southern Arizonaüåµ üåû. The U.S. Congress designated the Saguaro Wilderness in 1976 and it now has a total of 70,905 acres. The entirety of this wilderness is managed by the National Park Service and is bordered by the Rincon Mountain Wilderness to the east.<br>.<br>Saguaro Wilderness preserves thousands of acres of saguaro cactiüåµ . Sprouting in the shade of other desert plants, the saguaro cactus grows only a few inches in its first five years of life and a few feet in its first 30 years. At age 75 the cactus stands 15 to 20 feet tall and begins developing its first branches as it absorbs water through an extensive root system. A mature cactus can live up to 170 years, often measuring in at over 30 feet tall, weighing 6 to 10 tons, and holding one ton of water. The saguaro is truly the king of the Sonoran Desert.<br>.<br>Nearly 80% of Saguaro National Park has been designated Wilderness. Divided into two units by Tucson, the western Tucson Mountain Unit is relatively flat and the eastern Rincon Mountain Unit rises steeply in places from 2,800 feet to 8,666 feet on Mica Mountain ‚õ∞. Saguaro's Wilderness trail system contains approximately 127 miles of maintained trails ü•æ , but overnight camping is limited to six sites in the Rincon Mountains.<br>.<br>If you'd like to explore and give back to this particular Wilderness, check out the link in our bio for our 2022 Rincon Creek Trail, Saguaro National Park project. <br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#wildernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #saguarowilderness #designatedwilderness #wilderness #buffelgrass #invasiveplants #stewardship #conservation #nationalparkservice #nationalpark #findyourpark #saguaronationalpark #saguaro #saguaronationalparkwest #saguaronationalparkeast #saveoursaguaros #savethesaguaro #sonorandesert #optoutside #publicland #publiclands #leavenotrace #photography #camping #backpacking #colorpalette #colors #colorwheel

We hike for a few hours, planning on stopping at a campground that's ahead. I'm hoping for a general store to satisfy my snack hunger. At this point in the trail I crave anything that doesn't come in bar form. We get to the campground and look around, but doesn't seem to be the campsite we were hoping it would be. We couldn't find a general store or even administrative building. So we give up on that and just stop to eat lunch and dry our stuff out. We continue hiking, making a big elevation gain. We stop for pizzaritos (tomato sauce, pepperoni's, and cheese on a tortilla) at a water source- now that we're entering grizzly territory we're no longer eating where we camp. We then hike a little more, get frustrated from blowdowns, and set up camp.<br><br>Side note: In this pic is Squaretop Mountain, where if you're going northbound you have to turn around to see it, otherwise you'll completely miss it.<br><br>#newmexico #colorado #wyoming #idaho #montana #embracethebrutality #thetrek #hikingaddict #gooutside #staywild #hikertrash #continentaldividetrail #cdt2021 #mexicotocanada #backpacking #thruhike  #optoutside #camping #longdistancehiking #outdoors #choosemountains #LNT #leavenotrace #camp #summercamp #funnestknowntime

Fortunately the fire burned at mostly lower intensity through the groves. There were some losses in higher intensity strips which remind us that while the firs are excellently adapted to grow in rocky, fire-resistant places, the trees themselves are not fire resistant if flames find a way to reach them. Overall, the outcome was favorable for the Cone Peak groves, especially considering what could have happened, but the Santa Lucia Fir faces challenges including warming temperatures, drought, and more severe fires entering their fire resistant habitats. As the rarest fir in North America (and possibly the world) these inspiring, gorgeous trees merit protection, preservation and restoration where possible. #santaluciafir #abiesbracteata #keepitwild #ourwild #recreateresponsibly #leavenotrace

It Is something I think about every single time I post a photo - to tag or not to tag? <br><br>While I definitely don't have the answers, I do know a few things. <br><br>‚ú® Some of the worst offenders of LNT I have met have been people who grew up outdoors. Disrespectful people will be disrespectful. <br><br>‚ú® Not geotagging is exclusionary. While some people will have access to friends, family, or acquaintances who can help them find good places to recreate, lots of people do not have that circle built up. Just because some people have friends in the know does not mean they deserve the spaces any more than others.<br><br>‚ú® Crowded spots suck. It takes a ton of the magic away from the outdoors. BUT, to think that I have any more right to that space than anyone else is downright wrong. <br><br>‚ú® Ultimately, I have a lot to learn about being a good steward to the land. It is a privilege that I have the ability to visit, and I would argue that it's the case for *almost* everyone else out there as well. It is important to be introspective about yourself if you're going to point fingers at others. <br><br>‚ú® Geotagging can lead people to places they have no business being, from a safety perspective. Either because they don't know or have the correct equipment for the trip, or don't have the experience. This is the main reason I don't geotag some places. <br><br>Like I said, I definitely don't have the answers. This is just my musings, while I try to figure out what is right and wrong in  bringing others outside. <br><br>What do you think?<br><br>#optoutside #geotagging #geotag #keepwashingtonbeautiful #rei #nps #leavenotrace #recreateresponsibly #lnt #pnwhikingtrails #pnwbangers #northcascadesnationalpark #sheexplores #pnwbabes #womenoutdoors #outdoorwomen #upperleftusa #wanderlust #wta #alltrails #washingtontrailsassociation #outdoorsforall

Modern cairns are often erected to mark trails as landmarks, or to provide guidance on difficult routes.<br><br>‚ùóÔ∏èBefore you‚Äôre tempted to join in, please consider the following‚ùóÔ∏è<br><br>üß≠ An abundance of personal rock piles can cause confusion for hikers looking for navigational aids. Post_ID: 2764361169245060306	|Post_Code: CZc-9ZTvDzS	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 450	|Time_Stamp: 1643757552	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#navajo', '#dinetah', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine', '#modernoutdoors', '#natgeoyourshot', '#natgeotravelpic', '#Yourshotphotographer', '#OurPlanetDaily', '#lonelyplanet', '#mylpguide', '#usinterior', '#bealpha', '#divine']	|Caption: WC Petroglyphs 3, NM. This panel is a good example of older and newer glyphs being easy to differentiate. You can easily see the rectilinear glyphs and the small row of figures are lighter than most of the surrounding glyphs, making them younger in age. The exposed rock hasn‚Äôt had as much time to develop a new patina (also called desert varnish) as compared to the glyphs that have darkened. The general rule is as they get older, they get closer to matching the color of the rock surface they were pecked into. From what I‚Äôve seen with most sandstone petroglyphs, the oldest rock art is (usually) the same color as the surface it‚Äôs been pecked into. There ARE exceptions to this, especially with stone that hasn‚Äôt developed a patina on its surface. How about those flute players in Slides 2 & 3?!<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #navajo #dinetah #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

While you're hitting the trails, remember to respect the environment and leave no trace. What does leave no trace mean? We're glad you asked! It means leaving nothing but footprints and taking nothing but photos. Swipe through each photo to see how you can recreate responsibly, safely and enjoyably on the trails this winter! <br><br>1. Scoop the poop! Even in the winter, be sure to clean up after your pup.<br>2. Don't litter - trash is always uncovered when the snow melts. Also, it never hurts to pick up trash you may see.<br>3. Either translation is much cooler than the current name üòé Happy #mountainmonday<br><br>"Mount Washington is the largest mountain in New Hampshire and falls in the northern third of the Appalachian mountain range in a section called 'the Presidential Range.' The first European ascent of the mountain was performed in June of 1642 by Darby Field accompanied by two Native American guides. It is said that Field wanted to prove to the local Abenaki Chief Passaconaway that he was not subject to the same rules as the Indigenous peoples, who did not climb the summit of the mountain believed to be the realm of divine powers. By climbing the mountain Field dismissed these Indigenous beliefs and assisted the colonists‚Äô northern expansion." - the Indigenous NH Collaborative collective, https://indigenousnh.com/2018/12/06/the-wobanadenok/<br><br>Taken in January of 2022.

Post_ID: 2763496421851529987	|Post_Code: CZZ6VqihgMD	|Owner_ID: 2011066695	|Likes: 720	|Time_Stamp: 1643654466	|Tags: ['#LeaveNoTrace', '#Littering', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#FindYourPark', '#EncuentraTuParque']	|Caption: At Pinnacles, we often share the importance of Leaving No Trace and remembering to pack out any waste that you pack in during your visit to the park!<br><br>Most visitors are aware that leaving plastics or other inorganic materials on trail sides is harmful to the environment, but we often encounter discarded items that are thought of as 'biodegradable' strewn in the park, like orange peels or sunflower seed shells.<br><br>While this organic trash will decompose faster than plastic, it still poses a threat to our ecosystems, and creates a nuisance for fellow visitors.<br><br>Leaving food scraps along trails / park infrastructure can attract wildlife to areas of elevated human activity, increasing visitor-wildlife conflicts and habituating our wildlife to human contact.<br><br>As @leavenotraceorg explains, "One apple core will not completely disrupt the local ecosystem, but cumulatively, we know that feeding wildlife damages their health, alters their natural behaviors and exposes them to predators and other dangers."<br><br>When littering of food items occurs along road sides, wildlife feeding on the scraps can be hit by cars, or cause vehicles to swerve.<br><br>Help conserve our park's wildlife and improve the experience of your fellow visitors by always packing out any trash that you pack in, and ensuring that we all Leave No Trace when recreating in Pinnacles!<br><br>#LeaveNoTrace #Littering #RecreateResponsibly #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque <br><br>[Image Description: Fragments of orange peels lie on the ground along the Blue Oak Trail in Pinnacles National Park.]<br><br>Photo: NPS / Reuven Bank

This is especially so for outdoor sports, any activity where the experience and effects depend on nature. Running is instinctively enhanced by natural environments, the undulating terrain and fresh air bolster physical development and wellbeing. <br><br>This is why brands like @adidas have aligned their community and campaigns around #conservation‚Äîmost notably, #runwild‚Äîseeding support and education for #wildlife and ecological preservation through the love of running.<br><br>For the third edition of Run Wild‚Äîa global, ten-day digital running challenge, on the adidas Running app‚Äîathletes were invited to track their total distance (#running, #treadmill, #hiking, #walking, #virtualrunning, and #trailrunning) over ten days, comparing their progress to the range traveled by a wild #mountainlion named Gaia, currently roaming the Cascade Mountains in the U.S.A.‚Äôs Pacific Northwest. <br><br>Runners are virtually racing Gaia, while learning about #leavenotrace principles, #mindfulness, and #trailrunning from adidas athlete @timothyallenolson, who recently ran the fastest known time on the #pacificcresttrail. Timothy, @unep, and @adidasruntastic share insights on how runners can reconnect with their environment and act as responsible stewards of the outdoors. <br><br>By taking part in the Run Wild Challenge, #athletes also have the opportunity to support S.P.E.C.I.E.S. (carnivores.org), a conservation organization working to protect carnivores like Gaia and their habitats. <br><br>This is just one example of how a brand can capture and empower community support for nature‚Äîbravo adidas and all your runners!<br><br>Which brands inspire you with #wildhope?

Post_ID: 2762841308396301907	|Post_Code: CZXlYglvK5T	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 620	|Time_Stamp: 1643576371	|Tags: ['#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine', '#modernoutdoors', '#natgeoyourshot', '#natgeotravelpic', '#Yourshotphotographer', '#OurPlanetDaily', '#lonelyplanet', '#mylpguide', '#usinterior', '#bealpha', '#divine']	|Caption: Ancestral Structure, NM. One of my main tools for finding archaeological sites is Google Maps satellite view. I scan the landscape for any shapes that look man-made, primarily looking for hard angles and perfect circles. This spot was found using this method, and I made it out here and climbed up this extremely steep butte to get to the site. Once on top, I found the main structure I had spotted on Google Maps, made of stacked rocks with no mortar. I also found some lesser remnants of structures along the edges of the butte top, which was roughly 500‚Äô x 200‚Äô. I doubt anyone lived up here, and it looked like there may have been some burials judging by the few stone mounds I found topped with flat rocks. One even had a very faint inscription where I could just make out the words ‚ÄúI love you‚Äù. I decided not to take photos of that, and I left immediately after finding the possible graves. I think all of this is from the 18th-19th century, possibly even more modern. This butte may have been used for ceremonial purposes for generations, hence the older structure and the newer graves. Though this was on ‚Äúpublic land‚Äù, this is the Din√©tah, the Navajo homeland, and I understand that this ground is sacred. I walk these lands with reverence. There are many bones beneath us.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

We go to the local outfitter so Bison can buy new trekking poles (his second one broke the other day, and he couldn't pitch his tarp with just the bamboo pole). Taco (a hiker) offers us his room at the Jackalope motel to take a shower and do laundry. It's designed like a hunting lodge, so very up our alley. We then go to a food stand for dinner and the requisite ice cream, then resupply at the grocery store. A guy named Ridge in the store parking lot offers to take us back to the trailhead. We arrive at the trailhead and try to find a spot to camp at the campground. When we go out in nature, we always have an impact, and when many people visit a space, the collective impact can be significant. Here are some ways ‚ùó YOU ‚ùó can help minimize this impact and #LeaveNoTrace when you‚Äôre out in nature: <br>.<br>ü•æ Stay on the trail to avoid crushing plants and animals, damaging the landscape, and contributing to soil erosion. <br>.<br>üóëÔ∏è Take your waste with you. Throw it away in *designated* trash cans, or pack it out to throw away at home. Yes, EVEN organic/natural waste! (This includes banana peels, apple cores, orange peels, etc. as they can take years to breakdown.) <br>.<br>üì∏ Take ONLY photos and memories. Don‚Äôt pick flowers, pocket cool rocks or feathers. *Definitely* don‚Äôt bring home any animals. ‚ùåüö´ <br>.<br>ü¶å Don‚Äôt interact with wildlife. Don‚Äôt chase, feed, or attempt to touch animals. (Sure, that lizard is more scared of you than you are of it ‚Äì but that doesn‚Äôt mean it needs to be stressed out further!) <br>.<br>üëç Please be KIND, CONSIDERATE, and MINDFUL of other visitors. We ALL deserve the opportunity to enjoy our open spaces! üíö <br>.<br>Comment some other #LNT principles below, if you have them! <br>.<br>üì∑: @uy.woody <br>.<br>[Image description: A trail winds across lush green hillsides at dotted with trees] <br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#ilovenature #bayareatrails #californiahiking #climateresilience #hikesanjose #californianature #naturephotography #openspace #sanjoseca #savetheearth #santaclaravalley #southsanjose #sanjosenature #visitsanjose #mountainrange #santacruzmountains #ratherbehiking #hikingadventures #hikersofinstagram #perfecthike #hikingguide

The skies still look gray, so we don't bother waiting for our tents to dry before packing up. We plan on going to Pinedale, which requires hiking ten miles off trail to get to a campground to then hitch. Because of that, the path isn't on Guthook. We hike down the pass from our campsite and make it to the turn off. It starts to rain, and Bison and Nude Beach get ahead of me, so I don't have them to double check with we're on the right path. Luckily, there happens to be a lot of day hikers out so whenever I pass a group ask if I'm heading the right way. It's almost miserable hiking in the rain and not being entirely sure I'm on the right path, but I've got Cat Stevens playing in my headphones and as the youth say, "It's a vibe." I catch up to Bison and Nude Beach, and we run into Happy, Ontario, and Goddess. They found a shortcut, so we follow them. We encounter a train of llama-packers? We make it to the trailhead, and it takes us a while to get a hitch. A man and his son offer to take us as long as we're okay with stopping at some of the scenic spots along the way. We're not flush with choices, so we take them up on it and enjoy the overlooks! Once in town we immediately head into the Chinese restaurant and see El Dorado, 13, and Melon. We binge on Chinese food, go to the local park, dry everything out, look for spot to stealth camp (Just Sky July still in effect) and see a moose in the park we're hoping to sleep in (yay!). A thru-hikers enthusiast talks to us and buys us some beer! Once everything is dry we go and eat ice cream outside the grocery store. Nude Beach goes to the Jackalope Motel to sleep, Bison and I go to the park. Bison sets up his tarp for a quick tear down in the morning, and we attempt to get a good night's sleep.<br><br>#newmexico #colorado #wyoming #idaho #montana #embracethebrutality #thetrek #hikingaddict #gooutside #staywild #hikertrash #continentaldividetrail #cdt2021 #mexicotocanada #backpacking #thruhike  #optoutside #camping #longdistancehiking #outdoors #choosemountains #LNT #leavenotrace #camp #summercamp #funnestknowntime

I'm getting itchy to go on my next adventure, to the desert southwest once again. I went last year for the first time to attend the @outsidersphoto Photography Conference in Kanab, Utah. I flew into Vegas, went to a little out-of-the-way spot for the first 2 nights, then to the @valley.of.fire State Park for 3 nights. Had some lens issues and RV tire issues so I pretty much hung out in the campground after that. The park tried fixing two of them, but the other was very identifiable. <br> <br>I honestly don't understand why people would purposely go out to a beautiful spot to enjoy nature, then deface it "for fun". Boggles the mind. <br><br>Nature First principle "Always follow @leavenotraceorg principles and strive to leave places better than you found them." It is also one of Colorado's infamous 14ers, standing proudly at 14,115ft.  Located just a few minutes from Colorado Springs, this is one of the most easily accessible mountains in Colorado!  You can make your way to the summit via car, foot, bicycle, or the cog railway.<br>‚†Ä<br>‚è∞Park Hours:<br>9:00am-5:00pm (Oct 1-Thurs before Memorial Day)<br>7:30am-8:00pm (Fri before Memorial Day to Labor Day)<br>7:30am-7:00pm (Tues after Labor Day to Sept 30)<br>‚†Ä<br>üí≤ Entrance Fees:<br>Adults (16 and Over) - $15 per person (May-Nov) / $10 (Dec-Apr)<br>Children (6 to 15) - $5 per person<br>Carload Discount Rate (Up to 5 passengers) - $50 (May-Nov) / $35 (Dec-Apr)<br>‚†Ä<br>‚úîÔ∏è While the entire road is paved and well maintained, there are over 150 switchbacks and quite a bit a traffic. Plan for at least an hour to get from the entrance to the summit (and that is without making any stops).<br>‚†Ä<br>‚ùóÔ∏è When making your descent avoid overheating your breaks by downshifting to the lowest possible gear!  About halfway through your drive there will be a break check station where a ranger will check your break temperature and make you pull over for 15 min or so if they need to cool down.<br>‚†Ä<br>‚ùÑÔ∏è Regardless of when you go make sure to bring layers to bundle up in once you get towards to summit. Post_ID: 2761984405763884517	|Post_Code: CZUii70uYXl	|Owner_ID: 49483834901	|Likes: 19	|Time_Stamp: 1643474220	|Tags: ['#hiking', '#naturewalk', '#novicehiker', '#sedona', '#sedonaarizona', '#chickenpoint', '#explorearizona', '#leavenotrace', '#respectnature', '#trails', '#naturegram', '#midwestblogger', '#sdblogger', '#getoutside']	|Caption: Tips for novice hikers ü•æ‚õ∞Ô∏è<br><br>Now when I say novice hiker, I'm talking to my fellow Midwesterners who refer to the slightly hilly nature walk along the river of your local state park as a "hike."<br><br>It's all good. I'm right there with you! üòÖ They're all "hikes" to me too! But it is important to note that when you're traveling to more mountainous regions, the preparations you take for your hikes will look a little different.<br><br>So let's take a look at a few things to remember:<br><br>ü•æ Dress appropriately. Sturdy, snug fitting shoes. Breathable, moisture wicking clothing. And layers. Be prepared for temperature changes and your body's eventual heat up by dressing in layers!<br><br>ü•æ Plan ahead. Check the weather. Review a map of your trail beforehand. And if possible, download the map to your phone.<br><br>ü•æ Bring a backpack. On your nature walk through the Palisades, this may not be necessary. I mean, you can see the car from the middle of the trail! But when traveling longer distances over unfamiliar terrain, you're going to want a backpack of essentials.<br><br>ü•æ What essentials go in the backpack? A large bottle of water, snacks, and navigation equipment - map and compass, are a must. You may also want to consider the following: first aid kit, sunscreen, fire starter, blanket, flashlight, and power bank for portable charging.<br><br>ü•æ Finally, whether you're planning to enjoy the perfect summit beer, sit down for a picnic, or snarf down an energy bar, always, always remember to leave no trace! All trash and materials not from the area should be packed up and brought back with you for proper disposal. It's our responsibility to be good stewards of the earth and leave the land as we found it!<br><br>Happy hiking üòä<br><br>*Photos from Chicken Point, Sedona, AZ<br><br>#hiking #naturewalk #novicehiker #sedona #sedonaarizona #chickenpoint #explorearizona #leavenotrace #respectnature #trails #naturegram #midwestblogger #sdblogger #getoutside

Post_ID: 2761936197121436018	|Post_Code: CZUXlaBt2ly	|Owner_ID: 2228174887	|Likes: 399	|Time_Stamp: 1643468518	|Tags: ['#SustainableSaturday', '#visitusaparks', '#thisismyroute']	|Caption: Happy #SustainableSaturday! ‚Å†<br>‚Å†<br>This week we are bringing you some hiking etiquette tips! ü•æü•æü•æ‚Å†<br>‚Å†<br>1. Travel on durable surfaces (stay on-trail): Concentrating travel on trails reduces the likelihood that multiple routes will develop and scar the landscape. It is better to have one well-designed route than many poorly chosen paths. Lots of paths can lead to erosion, which can damage slopes and make it hard for vegetation to live there. üåæüåøüå±‚Å†<br>‚Å†<br>2. If you must go off-trail (this is usually only necessary in the backcountry), search for the most durable surfaces to walk on, so you leave less of an impact. Rocks, gravel snow and ice are the most durable to travel on (though beware in desert environments of cryptobiotic soil - this is created by living organisms such as algae, cyanobacteria, and fungi and takes hundreds of years to grow!). ü§Ø‚Å†<br>‚Å†<br>Traveling with respect through our beautiful wild spaces will help preserve and protect them for future generations. üåé üåç üåè‚Å†<br>‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>.‚Å†<br>üìçWestern Mono/Monache, Numu (Northern Paiute) and Eastern Mono/Monache land‚Å†<br> üì∑: @chrisslagle_ #visitusaparks #thisismyroute

Post_ID: 2761438803569482144	|Post_Code: CZSmfYLvRmg	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 541	|Time_Stamp: 1643409179	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#Utahspots', '#utahunique', '#youtah', '#utahisrad', '#Utahgram', '#visitutah', '#werutah', '#wowutah', '#naturalutah', '#utahillustrated', '#horse', '#equine', '#modernoutdoors', '#natgeoyourshot', '#natgeotravelpic', '#Yourshotphotographer', '#OurPlanetDaily', '#lonelyplanet', '#mylpguide', '#usinterior', '#bealpha', '#divine']	|Caption: MC Horses, UT. Have I mentioned how I‚Äôm a sucker for horse imagery? All of these are obviously historic, and they could have been made by a number of people- local indigenous, Mormon emigrants, ranchers, etc. They‚Äôre definitely old based on the patina returning to the exposed rock, and therefore they have historical relevance. Knowing who passed this way 100 or 200 years ago is much more interesting and informative in the sense you have to consider what life was like back then. They were moving livestock, mining, hunting, homesteading. There was almost always a purpose for someone to be out here, and it usually had something to do with surviving in this landscape. And they loved their horses, so much so that this guy made a portrait with him & his horse. Slide 2 is very lovingly drawn and quite anatomically accurate, though I think that truncated body is hilarious. Slide 3 is the most stylized of the bunch, and I love that the mane is depicted. I might have to start an Instagram just for horse petroglyphs.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #Utahspots #utahunique #youtah #utahisrad #Utahgram #visitutah #werutah #wowutah #naturalutah #utahillustrated #horse #equine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

For the most accurate weather forecast for your trip, navigate to Plan Your Visit from our home page, and click on Weather. This will take you to the National Weather Service forecast, which gives you the exact weather in the center of the park. <br><br>As Shawna explains, "other weather apps will show the weather in neighboring towns, which is usually 10-15F off. This makes a huge difference in the summer when it is 105F instead of 90F, or when it is 30F in the campground on a brisk winter‚Äôs night instead of a humid 45F."<br><br>Shawna recommends these additional website tips to help visitors plan their trip to Pinnacles:<br><br>‚óâ From the Plan Your Visit tab, you can select Things to Do. From here, visit the Hiking Trails tab to read detailed descriptions of the trails. <br><br>‚óâ From the Maps page in the navigation bar, you can view the park map and familiarize yourself with the trails and roadways prior to arrival. If you look closely at the map, you will notice little gray triangles at trail intersections. These triangles are areas on the trails where there will be signs indicating the trail names and distances. The numbers between these map markers indicate the mileage. <br><br>‚óâ Finally, click on the Alerts in Effect at the top of our page. It is updated regularly to reflect important operational changes that may impact your visit. <br><br>Check back next week when we'll be sharing Shawna's tips for how to pack safely for a hike in Pinnacles!<br><br>#PlanLikeAParkRanger #RecreateResponsibly #PlanForPinnacles #LeaveNoTrace <br><br>[Image Descriptions: The Balconies Cliffs surrounded by mist, followed by screenshots of the various pages of the park website described in the post above.]<br><br>Photo: NPS / Reuven Bank

Post_ID: 2761295964541885589	|Post_Code: CZSGAy-PRyV	|Owner_ID: 3544188636	|Likes: 154	|Time_Stamp: 1643392151	|Tags: ['#California', '#abandonedcalifornia', '#urbex', '#urbandecay', '#abandoned', '#forgotten', '#waterpark', '#desert', '#desertvibes', '#stories', '#vandalism', '#thisiswhywecanthavenicethings', '#leavenotrace', '#livetoexplore', '#wanderlust', '#urbanart', '#urbanphotography', '#abandonedplaces', '#abandoned', '#abandoned']	|Caption: In the 1950s local businessman Bob Byers began planning a lake for use by his extended family, which he named after his wife, Dolores. The lake was fed by underground springs that were, in turn, fed by the Mojave Aquifer. In 1962 a campground adjacent to the lake opened and travelers on highway 15 began to use the campground. Over the next 25 years, rides and attractions were added and Lake Dolores evolved into a waterpark dubbed "The Fun Spot in the Desert." After a downturn in popularity, the park closed in the late 1980s.<br>-<br>In 1990 Byers sold the park and the new owners recreated the park with a 50s theme, called Rock-a-Hoola waterpark which opened on July 4, 1998. The park quickly amassed $3 million dollars in debt and added a $4.4 MM dollar judgment to an employee who was paralyzed. The owners filed bankruptcy in 2000, and the park was eventually returned to Dolores Byers, whose husband had passed. Dolores sold the park in 2001 and died a month later.<br>-<br>After a 400,000 renovation the park reopened in May 2002 as Discovery Waterpark, but was only opened intermittently and closed for good in the summer of 2004. Many installations were sold off in 2009, including the slides, which became Colossal Canyon and Zero-60 Raceway at Cultus Lake Waterpark in B.C. Trespassers on the property stole metal and wires from the buildings, smashing sinks, toilets, and anything breakable, tagging over the 2013 artwork, and eventually setting the park on fire, burning many buildings to the ground in 2018.<br>-<br>In early 2020, a private investor bought the property and obtained conditional use permits to begin construction, but COVID hit. The park had been slated to reopen in 2023, but it appears plans are just delayed.<br>-<br>-<br>-<br>-<br>#California #abandonedcalifornia #urbex #urbandecay #abandoned #forgotten #waterpark #desert #desertvibes #stories #vandalism #thisiswhywecanthavenicethings #leavenotrace #livetoexplore #wanderlust #urbanart #urbanphotography #abandonedplaces #abandoned_junkies #abandoned_addiction

We collect them back for commercial composting.<br><br>It was a big decision for us when we started Eat Me Greens. In the end, we decided against recyclables , which would have been much cheaper for us. But often, public recycling ends up being shipped overseas under contract where it is often not handled correctly.<br><br>It seemed ludicrous that we would argue for low food miles but then have massive "waste miles" and even then for it all to be dumped in landfills anyway.<br><br>Whilst PLA will break down eventually in a landfill, it takes a long time. In an incinerator, they create less toxic residue than plastics. Compostables therefore, were the best option we could choose.<br><br>Commercial composting uses enzymes and correct pressure and temperature to make sure nothing is left for future generations to deal with.<br><br>We can't do it without you! Please return Eat Me Greens punnets to wherever you buy them, or message us directly to find out how we can get them back from you and dispose of them correctly.<br><br>#eatmegreens #plasticfree #plastic #plasticpollution #plantbased #pla #vegware #vegwareuk #plantsnotplastic #compost #composting #saynotoplastic #saynotosingleuseplastic #foodpackaging #planetorplastic #brentwoodessex #abridge #haveringattebower #staplefordabbotts #leavenotrace #microgreens

Post_ID: 2761248968170617229	|Post_Code: CZR7U6MOTmN	|Owner_ID: 35929030334	|Likes: 511	|Time_Stamp: 1643386549	|Tags: ['#leavenotrace', '#exploretheoutdoors', '#getoutside', '#exploremore', '#happypeoplehike', '#hikemoreworryless', '#sheexplores', '#hikingadventures', '#hikinggirl', '#adventureanywhere', '#womenwhohike', '#visitcolorado', '#optoutside']	|Caption: Happy Friday! <br><br>While hiking is now my favorite activity, I really only got serious about it a couple years ago. So today I want to share one of the most important things I think you should know about getting started hiking: the 7 principles of @leavenotraceorg!<br><br>The basics of leaving no trace as self explanatory - leave no evidence that you were there! But there are actually 7 principles provided by the Leave No Trace Center for Outdoor Ethics. <br><br>Leave what you find: This includes not taking rocks with you, not digging trenches for tents, not leaving anything behind and not damaging any live trees or plants (like by carving on a tree).<br><br>Plan ahead and prepare: Planning ahead will ensure your own safety and help you have a better time. Ways to plan ahead include checking the weather, understanding the terrain you‚Äôre visiting and having necessary items such as a map.<br><br>Dispose of waste properly: This not only includes trash, but human waste. Make sure you know ahead of time if waste should be packed out or it is allowed to be buried (this depends on the terrain). If you dig a hole, make sure it is out of the way of others and far from water sources. <br><br>Travel on durable surfaces: This means stay on the trail. Don‚Äôt take shortcuts as if it can damage fragile vegetation. <br><br>Minimize campfire impacts: Before building a fire, make sure you know the current fire danger in the area. It is always better to use fire rings that already exist when possible. <br><br>Respect wildlife: Never feed, bother or get too close to wildlife. Getting too close is not only dangerous to the animal but also to yourself. <br><br>Be considerate to others: Be considerate by not playing music on loud speakers, giving uphill hikers the right of way and keeping your pet in control if you bring one! <br><br>Save this post as a reminder!<br><br>How do you protect the landscape and minimize your impact when exploring the outdoors?<br><br>#leavenotrace #exploretheoutdoors #getoutside #exploremore #happypeoplehike #hikemoreworryless #sheexplores #hikingadventures #hikinggirl #adventureanywhere #womenwhohike #visitcolorado #optoutside

Post_ID: 2761202702763851797	|Post_Code: CZRwzqLFoAV	|Owner_ID: 41348624723	|Likes: 274	|Time_Stamp: 1643381034	|Tags: []	|Caption: Leave No Trace Principle 2: Travel and Camp on Durable Surfaces ‚¨áÔ∏è<br><br>Continuing with our LNT series, let‚Äôs talk about principle 2!<br><br>Choosing durable surfaces to travel and camp on greatly impacts the degradation of the environment. <br><br>ü•æRULE OF THUMB: stay on the provided trails. Trails are built to be able to limit the destruction of the nearby areas, to keep the traffic in a designated area. So, whenever possible, stay on the trail.<br><br>ü•æBUT, LET‚ÄôS BE REAL, there are times we have all gone off the trail! Whether you‚Äôre searching for a private ‚Äúbathroom‚Äù area, taking a lunch break,  finding a campsite, or scrambling up some rock to get to a vista, it‚Äôs just part of hiking! <br><br>ü™® Because of this, it‚Äôs important to BE CONSCIOUS of where you travel off trail. Rocky areas are often able to withstand a lot more travel than vegetation and living soil. <br><br>üë£ If you must travel through these areas, be conscious of your impact. (Sometimes this means spreading out from your group (vegetation), sometimes it means following exact footprints (soil))<br><br>üèïCAMPING on durable surfaces:<br>Choose a campsite that either already has very high traffic (no vegetation left) or, in less trafficked areas, find locations you can have the least impact on. Generally, rock and sand are great areas to set up camp, as they will be able to withstand campers. <br><br>‚õ∫Ô∏èü•òCAMP COOKING: Set up camp kitchens on Rocky areas to avoid constant trampling on vegetation and soil. <br><br>This principle is EXTENSIVE and every situation differs. Your situation changes in different locations, the type of trip, and the local environment. We highly recommend you go check out lnt.org for more information on how to implement this principle, but we hope this gave you a good idea of the general guidelines!<br><br>Overall, it is our jobs to take into consideration the environment around us to decide how we can best limit our impact on each trip.<br><br>We also feel it‚Äôs important to recognize that while ‚Äústay on the trail‚Äù is a good rule of thumb, there are circumstances when you just CAN‚ÄôT. Being able to know how to handle those moments and travel off trail responsibly is super important and can help us all to take better care of these lands!

More than 50% of nanoplastics found were PE, used in single-use plastic bags and packaging. Nanoplastics from tire wear were found in Greenland but not in Antarctica. <br><br>If you're interested in reading the whole study, check out Materiƒá et al., 2022, Environmental Research, or @guardian article "Nanoplastic pollution found at both of Earth's poles for first time".<br><br>#plasticene #plastics #microplastics #microplastic #nanoplastic #plasticsoup #marineplastics #sustainable #sustainability #climatechange #climatecrisis #noplanetb #leavenotrace #singleuse #earthdayeveryday #plasticplanet #science #environmentalawarness

Hordes of people descending on places like Alabama Hills in California and trashing them with no regard for the rights of others, or their long-term impacts. Post_ID: 2760774709887818583	|Post_Code: CZQPfivvttX	|Owner_ID: 38821492865	|Likes: 72	|Time_Stamp: 1643330013	|Tags: ['#fresnodoesntsuck']	|Caption: Sunny backpacking days are around the corner ü§òüèΩ Let‚Äôs talk about that little sign in the background, the one that says Leave No Trace. Some people like pages like these, and other people aren‚Äôt fans of them. While we don‚Äôt geo tag lesser known spots, we do try to tag the more well known areas & educate how to get outside in a responsible way. While there is a time to protect lesser known areas, a lot of times the outdoor community can be gatekeepers to places they don‚Äôt even own. The entire point of this page is that we live in a diverse community, the outdoor spaces nearby should reflect that diversity as well. Not just those who grew up with it or have the means to access it. <br><br>All that being said, when you head outdoors, whether it‚Äôs Woodward park down the road, or up to the snow at shaver, or to sequoia or yosemite national parks, we ask that you Leave No Trace. This means disposing of any trash you bring, what you pack in you pack out. Food wrappers, broken sleds, water bottles etc, pack it out to throw it away properly. Leave what you find. Whether it‚Äôs a rock or pine cone, let it stay at its home. Respect wildlife. Plan ahead. The only thing you should be leaving behind is footprints. If you want to learn more about exploring outdoor spaces in a respectful way visit @leavenotraceorg to learn more. Here‚Äôs to enjoying our parks & forests for years to come üôåüèºüçª #fresnodoesntsuck

Post_ID: 2760161525668706104	|Post_Code: CZOEEicLvc4	|Owner_ID: 2024810350	|Likes: 72	|Time_Stamp: 1643256916	|Tags: ['#oceanfriendlybusiness', '#oceanfriendly', '#takebackthetap', '#cutthecutlery', '#leavenotrace', '#livelikealocal', '#refill', '#circular', '#circulareconomy', '#surfrider', '#uclueletcampground', '#pacificrim', '#ucluelet', '#myucluelet', '#bethechange']	|Caption: Tucked away, off to the side of the heart of Ucluelet, is @uclueletcampground <br><br>Surfrider would like to recognize the exceptional efforts this local business has put into become an Ocean Friendly Business! <br><br>Founded in 1982, this campground, composed of 125 unique and forested sites sits along the waters edge.<br><br>The love of the ocean is clear and many steps have been taken to ensure waste reduction on site. <br><br>The transformed an old shed into their new recycling centre for guests accepting a range of items from cigarette butts to propane tanks. <br><br>They use icons and pictures, and have accessible stations as well to increase equity and inclusion of all guests, so that language and mobility are not hindering factors to waste diversion. <br><br>The Recycling centre is also home to a sharing library, where guests can leave unwanted supplies, such as tents, tarps, and other camping supplies for future guests. This sharing culture is part of a larger movement towards a circular economy, and moves away from the linear take-make-waste economy. <br><br>Since they created the recycling centre, they have reduced their waste by roughly 50%!! <br><br>The @uclueletcampground asks guests to follow a code of conduct, pledging to Take Back the Tap and refill reusable water bottles, leave no trace, and Cut the Cutlery, avoiding single-use cutlery and plates. <br><br>Beyond looking after the ocean, they donate all refundables, collected at the recycling centre, to feed the local community üíö<br><br>Thanks for being AWESOME Ucluelet Campground!! <br><br>üì∏ by @uclueletcampground <br><br>#oceanfriendlybusiness #oceanfriendly #takebackthetap #cutthecutlery #leavenotrace #livelikealocal #refill #circular #circulareconomy #surfrider #uclueletcampground #pacificrim #ucluelet #myucluelet #bethechange

Picture 2 shows the area after the soil has been decompacted to allow for aeration, moisture retention, and root growth. It was then covered in a layer of topsoil and dead vegetation. If left alone, this vegetation will start to decompose, adding necessary nutrients back into the soil and returning this patch to a healthy state. <br><br>Rangers and restoration crews work hard to return these areas to their natural state. If you see something that looks like picture 2, please leave it as is and find a more sustainable spot to stop!<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#restoration #rangers #jmt #johnmuirtrail #wildernessrestoration #sustainable #camping #natural #naturalization #leavenotrace #lnt

These concerns for women are legitimate and real. <br><br>Back in late October, before going into hibernation mode for winter, I got busted by a local landowner whilst setting up my tent in a corner of a field. It was dusk, my kit was out of the bag and I was caught peg-handed. He asked if I wanted to come in for dinner and my instincts - and rumbly tummy - said yes. He was a very wealthy man, insisting on telling me the price of most of the objects in his home. A tour of the house turned into what felt like an inventory! Clearly baffled at my choice to still sleep out in my tent - his house had many spare rooms and the weather was fierce - he still very kindly brought me a warm cup of tea in the morning to see me on my way. <br><br>That following evening, stretching beyond my comfort zone to camp in more of a remote spot than usual, turned out to be one of the most magical wild camps yet. After many hours walking and scouting, feet sore but spirits high, an ancient apple orchard was found, nestled on the edge of a field of monocrop. An encircling barrier of brambles provided plenty of cover, and snuggling down deep in my sleeping bag I looked up at a sky of a million stars. At some point much later a badger padded past, stopping to sniff the air beneath a moonlit dappled branch.
